{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"765f339e-828a-4b2f-946f-f1e71b6f3f48","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the Inspector via `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`) that proxies to your server over stdio.\n\n**In the Inspector UI you can:**\n- Browse **Tools**, **Resources**, and **Prompts** your server exposes\n- Execute tools with custom JSON inputs and see responses\n- Watch raw JSON-RPC messages in the **Messages** tab for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- If your server is already built, point to the DLL instead: `dotnet /path/to/YourServer.dll`\n- Add `--server-url` if you need to change the proxy port.\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and logs/diagnostics to **stderr** — anything else on stdout will break the protocol.\n- Set environment variables with `-e KEY=VALUE` flags if your server needs configuration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2258f9d3-9e43-4bbc-9ebf-8e9d44f4e32b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":328,"requestId":"B024:2D915E:CD243A:E9DA2B:6A027D38"},"id":"b8fb6d6a-2312-4da9-a960-fdd07799ed93","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:07:14.296Z","parentId":"fffdc23e-bbfd-41bf-a8bf-1ab6b2de755e"}
